</table>
<p>Every accredited Florida program is now doctoral-entry following the Council on Accreditation's January 1, 2025 phase-out of master's-level entry. Tuition across Florida programs generally runs $68,000–$125,000 total, with state universities (FIU, FSU, FGCU, UNF) typically cheaper for residents than private schools (Barry, Keiser, AdventHealth, University of Miami).</p>

<h2>University of Miami and FIU — South Florida</h2>
<p>The University of Miami's DNP nurse anesthesia program reported a 100% first-time certification pass rate for a recent cohort and runs clinicals across roughly 13 sites; the program starts in January each year. Florida International University's DNP-NA, housed in the Nicole Wertheim College of Nursing &amp; Health Sciences, is a strong public-university option in the same Miami market. South Florida's high surgical and trauma volume gives both programs excellent clinical depth, and Miami-area ICU nurses can often stay local for school.</p>

<h2>FSU, FGCU, and UNF — Statewide Public Options</h2>
<p>Florida State University has trained CRNAs since 2015 and runs its program with a Panama City clinical base. Florida Gulf Coast University in Fort Myers holds full COA accreditation through April 2032 and serves the southwest Florida market. The University of North Florida in Jacksonville offers a DNP track accredited through CCNE and draws North Florida and South Georgia applicants. For Florida residents, these public programs are typically the most cost-effective doctoral routes.</p>

<h2>AdventHealth, Barry, and Keiser — Private and Hybrid</h2>
<p>AdventHealth University in Orlando runs an intensive 36-month DNAP with Central Florida clinical sites. Barry University in Miami Shores delivers a portion of its DNP curriculum through distance-learning coursework, making it one of Florida's hybrid options. Keiser University offers a 90-credit, 36-month DNAP with a capstone and full clinical immersion. Private tuition is higher, but these programs add cohort capacity and scheduling formats that suit some working nurses better.</p>

<h2>Strong Florida ICU Hospitals for CRNA Applicants</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Hospital</th><th>Metro</th><th>Notable ICU Types</th></tr>
<tr><td>Jackson Memorial / Ryder Trauma</td><td>Miami</td><td>Level I Trauma, SICU, transplant ICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tampa General Hospital</td><td>Tampa</td><td>CVICU, Neuro ICU, transplant, Level I Trauma</td></tr>
<tr><td>UF Health Shands</td><td>Gainesville</td><td>Level I Trauma, CVICU, Neuro ICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>Orlando Regional Medical Center</td><td>Orlando</td><td>Level I Trauma, SICU, MICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>Memorial Regional Hospital</td><td>Hollywood</td><td>CVICU, MICU, high-acuity ICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>UF Health Jacksonville</td><td>Jacksonville</td><td>Level I Trauma, SICU, Neuro ICU</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Florida programs, like programs nationwide, want adult critical care managing ventilated, hemodynamically unstable patients on vasoactive drips with invasive lines. CVICU and trauma SICU roles at these academic and large-system hospitals build the strongest CRNA applications.</p>

<h2>The Application Timeline from Florida</h2>
<p>Florida programs vary in their cycles — University of Miami starts in January, while others start in summer or fall — so check each program's calendar carefully. In general, plan to apply 10–14 months before your intended start, with your CCRN done and ICU hours documented before applications open. With nine programs in-state, applying to three or four Florida schools plus one out-of-state option is a sound strategy for a competitive cycle.</p>

<div class="warning">
<strong>Cohort sizes are small:</strong> Florida programs admit roughly 24–60 students per cohort, and some (like Loma Linda-style competitive programs nationally) take far fewer. Small cohorts mean acceptance rates can be in the single digits. Do not anchor your entire plan on one Florida program — build a list, and strengthen the parts of your application (CCRN, GPA trend, shadowing, personal statement) that you control.
</div>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Florida CRNA salary on graduation:</strong> New CRNAs in Florida commonly earn $185,000–$215,000, with locum and independent contractor work reaching higher. Florida's surgical and procedural volume, driven partly by its older population, supports steady demand for anesthesia providers across the state. See the <a href="crna-school-requirements-2026.html">CRNA requirements guide</a> to benchmark your application.
</div>

